A03. Two Sum
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PROBLEM:
  Given a slice of integers and a target, return the indices of two numbers
  that add up to target. Assume exactly one solution exists.

APPROACH:
  Hash map: store value -> index as we iterate. For each number, check if
  (target - number) already exists in the map.

CODE:
  package main

  import "fmt"

  func twoSum(nums []int, target int) (int, int) {
      seen := make(map[int]int) // value -> index

      for i, num := range nums {
          complement := target - num
          if j, ok := seen[complement]; ok {
              return j, i
          }
          seen[num] = i
      }
      return -1, -1 // no solution
  }

  func main() {
      fmt.Println(twoSum([]int{2, 7, 11, 15}, 9))  // 0 1
      fmt.Println(twoSum([]int{3, 2, 4}, 6))        // 1 2
      fmt.Println(twoSum([]int{3, 3}, 6))            // 0 1
  }

COMPLEXITY:
  Time:  O(n)
  Space: O(n) — hash map

NOTE:
  Brute force is O(n²) — always mention the map optimisation first.

