  QUICK PATTERNS REFERENCE
================================================================================

  Two Pointers:
    Used for: palindrome, rotate, merge sorted
    Template: left, right := 0, len-1; for left < right { ... }

  Sliding Window:
    Used for: longest substring, max subarray
    Template: left := 0; for right := range s { shrink left as needed }

  Hash Map:
    Used for: two sum, anagrams, frequency, first unique
    Template: seen := make(map[K]V); for _, v := range input { ... }

  Fast & Slow Pointers:
    Used for: cycle detection, middle of list
    Template: slow, fast := head, head; fast != nil && fast.Next != nil

  Binary Search:
    Used for: sorted search, first/last position
    Template: left, right := 0, n-1; mid = left+(right-left)/2

  Worker Pool:
    Used for: concurrent job processing
    Template: jobCh + resultCh + N goroutines + WaitGroup

  Pipeline:
    Used for: multi-stage data processing
    Template: gen() -> stage1() -> stage2() -> collect

  Fan-out / Fan-in:
    Used for: parallel processing of same input
    Template: one input channel -> N worker channels -> merge()

================================================================================
  EDGE CASES TO ALWAYS MENTION
================================================================================

  Strings:
    - Empty string ""
    - Single character
    - Unicode / multi-byte characters (use []rune not []byte)

  Slices:
    - nil slice vs empty slice (len 0)
    - Single element
    - k > n in rotation (use k % n)

  Linked Lists:
    - nil head
    - Single node
    - Even vs odd length (middle node)

  Trees:
    - nil root
    - Single node tree
    - Unbalanced (left-skewed or right-skewed)

  Concurrency:
    - Goroutine leak — always have an exit path
    - Closed channel — ranging over closed channel is safe in Go
    - Buffered channel for non-blocking goroutine exit

